g2:c.METHOD.g2:a.TEXT:
jmail-send-mail-bundle(
  io: class jmail-interface,
  emails: sequence {a sequence of structure(
        sent-to: a sequence of text with the email addresses to send the mail to,
        cc: a sequence of text with the 'cc' email addresses,
        bcc: a sequence of text with the 'bcc' email addresses,
        subject: text with the subject of the mail,
        contents: text with the contents of the mail)}) =
    (text {Result. Will return "OK" if operation was successfull. Otherwise, it will contain an error- message})

{
This method will send a bundle of emails within one 'session'. This might be more efficient in case of sending larger amounts of emails since it requires only one session authentication. 

In the current JMail Bridge implementation, the protocol is always 'smtp'.  It wil use the following attributes of the jmail-interface:
  outgoing-email-host 
  user-name 
  password 
  outgoing-email-from-address 
}

  list-of-emails: sequence = sequence ();
  email: structure; 

  result: text = "Not connected"; 

begin

  { --- Add from and ensure that cc and bcc are defined. send-to, subject and contents should always be defined by the caller }
  for email = each structure in emails do

    email = change-attribute (email, from, the outgoing-email-from-address of io);

    if the cc of email does not exist then
      email = change-attribute (email, cc, sequence ( ));

    if the bcc of email does not exist then
      email = change-attribute (email, bcc, sequence ( ));

    list-of-emails = insert-at-end (list-of-emails, email);
  end; 

  if the gsi-interface-status of io = 2 then
    result = call _jmail-rpc-send-mail-bundle(_jmail-gsi-config(io), the outgoing-email-protocol of io, the outgoing-email-host of io, the outgoing-email-host-port of io, the outgoing-email-ssl-enable of io, the user-name of io, the password of io, list-of-emails) across io; 

  return result;

end

jmail-send-mail (
  io: class jmail-interface,
  smtp-host: text,
  username: text,
  password: text,
  to-email-addresses: sequence,
  cc-email-addresses: sequence,
  from-email-address: text,
  subject: text,
  contents: text) =
    (text {result. "OK" is good})

{
Low-level api to call the rpc in the jmail-bridge directly. For explanation of the arguments see the documentation of the attributes of jmail-interface and the 'high-level' method jmail-interface::jmail-send-mail. Expects the mail server to use the default port 25.
} 

  result: text; 

begin

  result = call jmail-send-mail(io, smtp-host, the outgoing-email-host-port of io, username, password, to-email-addresses, cc-email-addresses, from-email-address, subject, contents);
  return result;

end

jmail-get-mail (
  IO: class jmail-interface, {The gsi interface to use} 
  Protocol: text, {Receiving protocol. }
  smtp-host: text {Mail server },
  username: text {Mail server username }, 
  password: text {Mail server username password },
  folder: text {Mail server forlder },
  delete-messages: truth-value {If True delete retrieved messages},
  maximum-number-of-messages: integer {Maximum number of messages to retrieve},
  maximum-message-length: integer {Maximum length of messages to return., If messages are longer, they are truncated.}) =
    (sequence {list of e-mail messages. Each email is encapsulated in a structure})

{
Low-level api to call the rpc in the jmail-bridge directly. For explanation of the arguments see the documentation of the attributes of jmail-interface and the 'high-level' method jmail-interface::jmail-get-mail. Expects the email server to use the default port 25.
}

  emails: sequence;

begin

  emails = call jmail-get-mail(io, protocol, smtp-host, the incoming-email-host-port of io, username, password, folder, delete-messages, maximum-number-of-messages, maximum-message-length);

  return emails;

end

jmail-send-mail( io: class jmail-interface, to-email-addresses: sequence {a sequence of text with the email addresses to send the mail to}, cc-email-addresses: sequence {a sequence of text with the 'cc' email addresses}, subject: text {the subject of the mail}, contents: text {the contents of the mail}) = (text {Result. Will return "OK" if operation was successfull. Otherwise, it will contain an error- message})
{ This method will send an email in MIME text format. In the current JMail bridge implementation, the protocol used to send email messages is always 'smtp'. It wil use the following attributes of the jmail-interface:
outgoing-email-host user-name password outgoing-email-from-address }
result: text = "Not connected";
begin
if the gsi-interface-status of io = 2 then result = call _jmail-rpc-send-mail(_jmail-gsi-config(io), the outgoing-email-protocol of io, the outgoing-email-host of io, the outgoing-email-host-port of io, the outgoing-email-ssl-enable of io, the user-name of io, the password of io, to-email-addresses, cc-email-addresses, sequence ( ), the outgoing-email-from-address of io, subject, contents) across io;
return result;
end

jmail-get-mail( io: class jmail-interface, maximum-number-of-messages: integer, maximum-message-length: integer ) = (sequence {of structure(from-email-address: sequence(text), sent-to: sequence(text), cc-email-addresses: sequence(text), received-date: text, sent-date: text, subject: text, contents: text, recent-flag: truth-value, seen-flag: truth-value, deleted-flag: truth-value)})
{ This method will get e-mail based on the following attributes of the jmail-interface:
incoming-email-protocol (only 'pop3' has been tested so far), incoming-email-host , user-name , password , incoming-email-folder (in case of pop3 this should be and can only be "INBOX"), incoming-email-delete-messages-on-host ,
It returns a sequence of 'email-structures'. An email-structure consists of the following attributes:
from-email-address: a sequence of text, sent-to: a sequence of text, cc-email-addresses: a sequence of text, received-date: a text, sent-date: a text. subject: a text. contents: a text. recent-flag: a truth-value, seen-flag: a truth-value, deleted-flag: a truth-value, content-truncated: a truth-value (true if the contents was truncated because it exeeded the maximum length), content-is-plain-text: a truth-value (for any message which is not of mime-type 'text/plain', the contents will be an empty string and this flag is set to true).
The dates are formatted by :"YYYYMMDD HH24MMSS". Note that pop3 does not seem to support the received-date or any of the 'flags'. The JMail bridge simply passes the information generatred by the jmail bridge to G2. Be carefull when interpretating the results. }
emails: sequence = sequence ( );
begin
if the gsi-interface-status of io = 2 then emails = call _jmail-rpc-get-mail(_jmail-gsi-config(io), the incoming-email-protocol of io, the incoming-email-host of io, the incoming-email-host-port of io, the incoming-email-ssl-enable of io, the user-name of io, the password of io, the incoming-email-folder of io, the incoming-email-delete-messages-on-host of io, maximum-number-of-messages, maximum-message-length) across io;
return emails;
end

jmail-disconnect (io: class jmail-interface)

begin

  if the gsi-interface-status of io = 2 then
    start _jmail-rpc-shutdown() across io;

  wait for 0.05 seconds;

  change the text of the gsi-connection-configuration of io to "None";
end

